<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-graphing-circles" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Graphing Circles</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.6 Graphical Methods
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                            <ul>
                              <li>Determine the centre, radius and equation of a circle in different situations</li>
                              <li>Draw graphs of circles and parabolas in different situations</li>
                            </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>
                        15 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Objective</title>
                    <p>
                        To discover the relationship between the coordinates of points on a circle and its center and radius using the distance formula.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                    <p>
                        Guide learners to use a compass or a piece of string to maintain a constant distance from a fixed point. Encourage them to apply the Pythagorean theorem or distance formula to generalize their findings.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in Groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>What you need</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Graph paper
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A compass or a piece of string and a pencil
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A ruler
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                Imagine you have a fixed point <m>C(2, 3)</m> on a coordinate plane. You want to find all points <m>P(x, y)</m> that are exactly 5 units away from <m>C</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>What to do</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Plot the point <m>C(2, 3)</m> on a grid.
                        </p>
                        <image width="40%">
                            <latex-image label="fig-activity-center">
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, step=1] (-5,-4) grid (9,10);
                                    \draw[-&gt;] (-5,0) -- (9,0) node[right] {$x$};
                                    \draw[-&gt;] (0,-4) -- (0,10) node[above] {$y$};
                                    \foreach \x in {-4,-2,2,4,6,8} \draw (\x,2pt) -- (\x,-2pt) node[below] {\footnotesize $\x$};
                                    \foreach \y in {-2,2,4,6,8} \draw (2pt,\y) -- (-2pt,\y) node[left] {\footnotesize $\y$};
                                    \filldraw (2,3) circle (2pt) node[above right] {$C(2,3)$};
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>      
                        </image>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Mark at least <m>8</m> points that are exactly <m>5</m> units away from <m>C</m>. (Hint: Think of points directly above, below, left, and right, and some in between using Pythagorean triples like 3, 4, 5).
                        </p>
                        <image width="40%">
                            <latex-image label="fig-activity-points">
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, step=1] (-5,-4) grid (9,10);
                                    \draw[-&gt;] (-5,0) -- (9,0) node[right] {$x$};
                                    \draw[-&gt;] (0,-4) -- (0,10) node[above] {$y$};
                                    \foreach \x in {-4,-2,2,4,6,8} \draw (\x,2pt) -- (\x,-2pt) node[below] {\footnotesize $\x$};
                                    \foreach \y in {-2,2,4,6,8} \draw (2pt,\y) -- (-2pt,\y) node[left] {\footnotesize $\y$};
                                    \filldraw (2,3) circle (2pt) node[above right] {$C(2,3)$};
                                    \foreach \p in {(7,3), (-3,3), (2,8), (2,-2), (5,7), (-1,7), (5,-1), (-1,-1)}
                                        \filldraw \p circle (1.5pt);
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>   
                        </image>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Connect these points smoothly. What shape do you get?
                        </p>
                        <image width="40%">
                            <latex-image label="fig-activity-circle">
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, step=1] (-5,-4) grid (9,10);
                                    \draw[-&gt;] (-5,0) -- (9,0) node[right] {$x$};
                                    \draw[-&gt;] (0,-4) -- (0,10) node[above] {$y$};
                                    \foreach \x in {-4,-2,2,4,6,8} \draw (\x,2pt) -- (\x,-2pt) node[below] {\footnotesize $\x$};
                                    \foreach \y in {-2,2,4,6,8} \draw (2pt,\y) -- (-2pt,\y) node[left] {\footnotesize $\y$};
                                    \filldraw (2,3) circle (2pt) node[above right] {$C(2,3)$};
                                    \draw[blue, thick] (2,3) circle (5);
                                    \foreach \p in {(7,3), (-3,3), (2,8), (2,-2), (5,7), (-1,7), (5,-1), (-1,-1)}
                                        \filldraw \p circle (1.5pt);
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Use the distance formula to write an expression for the distance between <m>C(2, 3)</m> and any point <m>P(x, y)</m> on this shape.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Set this distance expression equal to <m>5</m> and square both sides. What equation do you get?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            What do you notice about the equation you derived? How does it relate to the points you plotted?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Share your work with the class.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize the definition of a circle and derive its standard equation.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> Refer to the activity where learners found that the distance from <m>(2, 3)</m> to <m>(x, y)</m> is <m>d = \sqrt{(x - 2)^2 + (y - 3)^2}</m>. Setting <m>d = 5</m> and squaring gives <m>(x - 2)^2 + (y - 3)^2 = 25</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Generalization:</alert> Explain that for any center <m>(h, k)</m> and radius <m>r</m>, the equation is <m>(x - h)^2 + (y - k)^2 = r^2</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p>
            A <term>circle</term> is the set of all points in a plane that are at a constant distance, called the <term>radius</term> (<m>r</m>), from a fixed point called the <term>center</term> (<m>h, k</m>).
        </p>
        <p>
            The <term>standard equation</term> of a circle with center <m>(h, k)</m> and radius <m>r</m> is:
            <me>(x - h)^2 + (y - k)^2 = r^2</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            If the center is at the origin <m>(0, 0)</m>, the equation simplifies to:
            <me>x^2 + y^2 = r^2</me>
        </p>
        <p>
        <alert> How to Graph a Circle </alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            To graph a circle from its standard equation <m>(x - h)^2 + (y - k)^2 = r^2</m>, follow these steps:
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <alert>Identify the Center:</alert> The center is the point <m>(h, k)</m>. Note that the signs in the equation are negative, so if you see <m>(x + 2)</m>, then <m>h = -2</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <alert>Identify the Radius:</alert> The constant term on the right is <m>r^2</m>. Take the square root to find the radius <m>r</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <alert>Plot the Center:</alert> Mark the point <m>(h, k)</m> on the coordinate plane.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <alert>Plot Four Key Points:</alert> From the center, move <m>r</m> units in four directions:
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Up: <m>(h, k + r)</m></p></li>
                        <li><p>Down: <m>(h, k - r)</m></p></li>
                        <li><p>Left: <m>(h - r, k)</m></p></li>
                        <li><p>Right: <m>(h + r, k)</m></p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <alert>Draw the Circle:</alert> Connect these four points with a smooth, round curve.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </insight> 

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the equation of a circle with center <m>(0, 0)</m> and radius <m>4</m> units. Sketch its graph.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Since the center is at the origin <m>(0, 0)</m>, we use the simplified equation <m>x^2 + y^2 = r^2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Given <m>r = 4</m>, we have:
                <me>x^2 + y^2 = 4^2</me>
                <me>x^2 + y^2 = 16</me>
            </p>
                <image xml:id="img-example-origin" width="40%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, step=1] (-5,-5) grid (5,5);
                            \draw[-&gt;] (-5,0) -- (5,0) node[right] {$x$};
                            \draw[-&gt;] (0,-5) -- (0,5) node[above] {$y$};
                            \filldraw (0,0) circle (2pt) node[above right] {$(0,0)$};
                            \draw[blue, thick] (0,0) circle (4);
                            \filldraw (4,0) circle (1.5pt) node[below right] {$(4,0)$};
                            \filldraw (-4,0) circle (1.5pt) node[below left] {$(-4,0)$};
                            \filldraw (0,4) circle (1.5pt) node[above left] {$(0,4)$};
                            \filldraw (0,-4) circle (1.5pt) node[below left] {$(0,-4)$};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the equation of a circle with center <m>(-2, 5)</m> and radius <m>3</m> units.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                We use the standard equation <m>(x - h)^2 + (y - k)^2 = r^2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Here, <m>h = -2</m>, <m>k = 5</m>, and <m>r = 3</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Substituting these values:
                <me>(x - (-2))^2 + (y - 5)^2 = 3^2</me>
                <me>(x + 2)^2 + (y - 5)^2 = 9</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Identify the center and radius of the circle with equation <m>(x - 3)^2 + (y + 4)^2 = 25</m>. Sketch its graph.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Comparing <m>(x - 3)^2 + (y + 4)^2 = 25</m> with <m>(x - h)^2 + (y - k)^2 = r^2</m>:
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>h = 3</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>k = -4</m> (since <m>y + 4 = y - (-4)</m>)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>r^2 = 25 \Rightarrow r = \sqrt{25} = 5</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                The center is <m>(3, -4)</m> and the radius is <m>5</m>.
            </p>
                <image xml:id="img-example-h-k" width="40%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, step=1] (-3,-10) grid (9,2);
                            \draw[-&gt;] (-3,0) -- (9,0) node[right] {$x$};
                            \draw[-&gt;] (0,-10) -- (0,2) node[above] {$y$};
                            \filldraw (3,-4) circle (2pt) node[above right] {$(3,-4)$};
                            \draw[blue, thick] (3,-4) circle (5);
                            \filldraw (8,-4) circle (1.5pt);
                            \filldraw (-2,-4) circle (1.5pt);
                            \filldraw (3,1) circle (1.5pt);
                            \filldraw (3,-9) circle (1.5pt);
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            <p>
                To sketch the graph:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Plot the center <m>(3, -4)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Move 5 units up, down, left, and right from the center to find four points on the circle: <m>(3, 1), (3, -9), (-2, -4), (8, -4)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Draw a smooth circle passing through these points.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Identify the correct equation for the graph below:
            </p>
            <image width="40%">
                <latex-image label="fig-example-multiple-choice">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, step=1] (-5,-10) grid (7,4);
                        \draw[-&gt;] (-5,0) -- (7,0) node[right] {$x$};
                        \draw[-&gt;] (0,-10) -- (0,4) node[above] {$y$};
                        \filldraw (1,-2) circle (2pt) node[above right] {$(1,-2)$};
                        \draw[blue, thick] (1,-2) circle (6);
                        \filldraw (7,-2) circle (1.5pt);
                        \filldraw (-5,-2) circle (1.5pt);
                        \filldraw (1,4) circle (1.5pt);
                        \filldraw (1,-8) circle (1.5pt);
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                
            </image>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m> y^2 = x^2 + 6^2 </m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>(x - 1)^2 + (y + 2)^2 = 36</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>(x + 1)^2 + (y - 2)^2 = 36</m>
                        </p>        
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>(x - 1)^2 + (y - 2)^2 = 36</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Identify an <m>x^2</m> term and <m>y^2</m> term.
            </p>
            <p>
                The equation must be in the form <m>(x - h)^2 + (y - k)^2 = r^2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                The center is <m>(1, -2)</m>, so <m>h = 1</m> and <m>k = -2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                The radius is 6, so <m>r^2 = 36</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Substituting these values gives:
                <me>(x - 1)^2 + (y - (-2))^2 = 36</me>
                <me>(x - 1)^2 + (y + 2)^2 = 36</me>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, the correct equation is <m>(x - 1)^2 + (y + 2)^2 = 36</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

